<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05177b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05177b">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05177b"> 177(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> fiddler remember when propped / &amp; using bow crutch</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">He extracted one excellent tune from a one-legged man who had played the fiddle in his youth, and could not be got to remember the air in question <mark>till he had propped himself up against the wall, and had drawn his crutch for a long time across his shoulder</mark>, as if playing upon the long-disused instrument. With the air thus recovered in his head, he found himself able to hum it to Mr. Gill. <small> Alfred Perceval Graves, <a name="ILMS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ILMS"><cite title="source">Irish Literary and Musical Studies</cite></a>, (1913) [Folk Song] 180</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
